Correspondent Dominic Cunningham-Reid speaks with diamond miners in the West African nation of Sierra Leone, a country emerging from a ten-year civil war. A serendipitous product of the enormous heat and pressure exerted upon graphite deep beneath the earth, diamonds are the world\&amp;#039;s most sought-after stone. Despite their role as an international symbol of love and affection, diamonds have financed the brutal civil war in Sierra Leone and other African countries.

